The beardless youth, having at last got rid of his guardian, is happy with his horses and dogs, and in the sports of the sunny campus; his mind, like wax, is solt and easy to be formed to vice, froward to his reprovers, slow in providing for the needs of life, lavish of his money, high-spirited, amorous, and hasty in abandoning the objeets of his love.

Our inclinations changing with our yearS, the temper of middle life is eager in pursuit of riches, and seeks to multiply friends, is ambitious of honour, and cautious of venturing on an action which soon might need to be undone.

Many infirmities beset old age; either because an old man is too anxious for gain, and yet pinches liQimself, and is afraid to use his money; or because he does everything with a chilled and listless spirit, being dilatory, languid in hope, remiss, greedy of a longer lite, peevish, apt to repine‚ praising ever the former days when he was a boy, censuring and forever correcting those who are younger than himself.
